nctions.php in Themes?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:98:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/12/04/how-often-do-you-use-functions-php-in-themes/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:98:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/12/04/how-often-do-you-use-functions-php-in-themes/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2991:"<p>Before I start, I must say that this question is directed more towards advanced users, rather than users who donâ€™t fiddle with their themes.</p>\n<p>As a advanced user of both WordPress and PHP, I prefer to keep things to the minimal and make use of existing features rather than adding new ones that overlap.</p>\n<p>For example, I wanted to use the Bit.ly API to shorten URLs and track them. Instead of using a plugin I could create for my use or use existing ones, I preferred to add a new method to the functions.php of my theme. For those who are interested, you can find the code below.</p>\n<pre>define(''TB_BIT_API_USER'', ''username'');\ndefine(''TB_BIT_API_KEY'', ''apikey'');\nfunction tb_make_bitly_url($postid, $url, $format = ''xml'') {\n  $shorturl = get_post_meta($postid, "shortened_url", true);\n  if(!$shorturl) {\n    $bitly = ''http://api.bit.ly/shorten?longUrl=''.urlencode($url).''&amp;login=''.TB_BIT_API_USER.''&amp;apiKey=''.TB_BIT_API_KEY.''&amp;format=''.$format.''&amp;version=2.0.1&amp;history=1'';\n    try {\n      $httpclient = new WP_Http;\n      $response = $httpclient-&gt;request($bitly);\n      $xml = simplexml_load_string($response[''body'']);\n      $shorturl = ''http://bit.ly/''.$xml-&gt;results-&gt;nodeKeyVal-&gt;hash;\n      add_post_meta($postid, "shortened_url", $shorturl);\n    }\n    catch(Exception $e) {\n      $shorturl = $url;\n    }\n  }\n  return $shorturl;\n}</pre>\n<p>Functions.php should generally be used when you just want to add a minor feature that requires a single function or few lines of code. However, you cannot use functions.php to run code in the actions such as â€œplugins_loadedâ€, which run before the theme is loaded, you can however add code to other actions which run after the theme is loaded. This is by design and should be too, as each theme will have their own functions.php file and should only perform functions that relate to displaying the website.</p>\n<p>Theme developers can use Functions.php to include common methods like getting recent posts or comments and so on instead of including additional plugins. Of course giving due credit wherever required is of utmost importance too.</p>\n<p>I had written a post earlier, whether or not it made difference <a href="http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/06/19/wordpress-plugins-usage-faqs/" target="_blank">If you use 1 plugin or 100 plugins</a> which can give you a general idea on what benefits you can get by using functions.php for smaller functions. It is still debatable, but you can always run benchmarks to find which the best method is.</p>\n<p>Of course, users who edit themes themselves will have a minor problem if they keep changing their themes, as functions.php is different for each theme. I usually create a new file called â€œcustomfunctions.phpâ€ and then include it in the functions.php to keep things short and sweet and reusable.</p>\n<p>Do you prefer to add code to functions.php or prefer using plugins for small tasks? Do let me know your thoughts about it.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 05 Dec 2009 02:07:42 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Keith Dsouza";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:41;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"Weblog Tools Collection: WordPress Theme Releases for 12/04";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=7318";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:87:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/12/04/wordpress-theme-releases-for-1204/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1713:"<h4><a href="http://www.slimmity.com/2009/12/free-wp-theme-simpleblog/">SimpleBlog</a></h4>\n<p><a href="http://slimmity.com/go/simpleblog"><img title="SimpleBlog" src="http://weblogtoolscollection.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/SimpleBlog.png" alt="SimpleBlog" width="200" height="106" /></a></p>\n<p>Doesn&#8217;t contain many features nor does it have preloaded plugins other then WP-PageNai. It has a small option page where you can edit the logo and favicon url&#8217;s, from this page you can also add your feedburner url and twitter account that will be displayed on the custom sidebar widget called: RSS Feed Suscribe. It has all the basic html elements styled for posts and the sidebar is widget ready.</p>\n<h4><a href="http://www.blogging-inside.de/2009/11/blueskyline-theme-fuer-wordpress/">BlueSkyLine</a></h4>\n<p><img title="blueskyline" src="http://weblogtoolscollection.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/blueskyline.jpg" alt="blueskyline" width="200" height="122" /></p>\n<p>BlueSkyline is a simple WordPress Theme with one Sidebar and Widget Support. There is an Option Page to populate the Footer.</p>\n<h4><a href="http://www.blogging-inside.de/2009/12/redcity-theme-fuer-wordpress-mit-4-widget-zonen/">RedCity</a></h4>\n<p><img title="Redcity" src="http://weblogtoolscollection.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/Redcity.gif" alt="Redcity" width="200" height="120" /></p>\n<p>RedCity is a WordPress Theme with two Sidebars, one Topbar and one Footerbar for Ads or whatever Widget you want to place there and Widget Support. There is an Option Page to populate the Footer.</p>\n<p>Are you a theme author? <a href="http://weblogtoolscollection.com/submit-news/">Submit your theme</a> to get it listed here.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 04 Dec 2009 20:40:44 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"Perurry";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:42;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:52:"Weblog Tools Collection: Do You Use The Code Editor?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=7310";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/12/04/do-you-use-the-code-editor/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1901:"<p>The code editor. One for plugins and one for themes. If I were using tracking software, it would register me as rarely venturing into that part of the WordPress administration. I&#8217;ve used WordPress for two years and I&#8217;ve burned myself enough times by using these code editors that I neglect to use them anymore side from looking but not touching code. The biggest problem I have is that it doesn&#8217;t contain any revisions. Also, when you click the save button, it reloads the page and causes the scroll bar in the code window to go back to the top meaning I have to remember which line of code I was editing and also remember the change I implemented so I can remove it if I don&#8217;t like the desired effects. </p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve really come to appreciate using Control Z on my keyboard to undo changes I don&#8217;t like. You can&#8217;t do a Control Z after you click the save button in the editor which again, brings me back to my complaint of no revisions. When CodePress was introduced, I thought it was cool and a much-needed upgrade over the current implementation. However, I love NotePad++ and the ability to play around with a local copy of my site by editing the files directly within a good editor instead of through WordPress. </p>\n<p>It&#8217;s my opinion that those who know what they are doing use their favorite tool and then upload the changes rather than the built-in code editor. I&#8217;m going to take a guess and say that end users make up the majority of the user base for WordPress and that this user base is not so inclined to use the editor to change code around. Therefor, I&#8217;m hoping to hear some valid reasons as to why it should be kept in WordPress.</p>\n<p><center><br />\n<a href="http://answers.polldaddy.com/poll/2340096/">Do You Use The Code Editor?</a><span>(<a href="http://www.polldaddy.com">online surveys</a>)</span><br />\n</center></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 04 Dec 2009 15:33:26 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Jeff Chandler";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:43;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:67:"WordPress.tv: Justin Shreve: Building a Better Search for WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:27:"http://wordpress.tv/?p=3127";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"http://wordpress.tv/2009/11/14/justin-shreve-search-nyc09/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1375:"<div class="snap_preview"><br /><ins>\n<div class="video-player" id="x-video-10">\n</div></ins>\n<br /><a href="http://wordpress.tv/2009/11/14/justin-shreve-search-nyc09/"><img width="160" height="120" src="http://cdn.videos.wordpress.com/WriJLRuF/search_api_std.original.jpg" alt="" /></a>  <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/wptv.wordpress.com/3127/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/wptv.wordpress.com/3127/" /></a> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/wptv.wordpress.com/3127/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/wptv.wordpress.com/3127/" /></a> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/wptv.wordpress.com/3127/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/w