South Africa and Colombia are available for purchase on <a href="http://www.etsy.com/shop/elleeffect">Etsy</a> to support\r\nthe organizations she has worked with.\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:center;"><strong>worldwide projects</strong>:\r\n<em><a href="http://pfunanane.org/">pfunanane academy</a>, south africa</em> : oct-dec 2008\r\n<em><a href="http://openarmsfoundation.wordpress.com/">open arms foundation</a>, medellin, colombia</em> : july 2009\r\n<em>oaxaca, mexico</em> : summer 2010\r\n<em>bangalore, india</em> : TBA\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:center;"><em><strong>To read more detailed writing and thoughts</strong>:\r\n</em><a href="http://elleeffect.wordpress.com/"><span style="font-size: large;">ÏÎ¯Î¶Î±</span></a>\r\n<p style="text-align:center;"></p>', 'about', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'about', '', '', '2009-12-13 16:21:51', '2009-12-14 00:21:51', '', 0, 'http://www.elleeffect.com/?page_id=1114', 0, 'page', '', 12);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(144, 2, '2007-06-08 14:30:43', '2007-06-08 14:30:43', '<a href="http://flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/532492637/"></a>\n<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/532492637/"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/532492637_2319a546e3.jpg" alt="" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align:center;">Â </p>\n<p style="text-align:center;">I''ve been keeping to myself lately. Really living into having a quiet heart. When I''m nervous, I lick my lips a lot. This is somewhat of a nerve-shaking time of transition (which is very beautiful and thrilling) - meaning in my heart, I''m licking my lips... making them chapped.</p>\n<p style="text-align:center;">Â </p>\n<p style="text-align:center;">I started a new painting today. I''ll be posting my progress.</p>\n<p style="text-align:center;">-lauren</p>', 'chapped lips', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'chapped-lips', '', '', '2007-06-08 14:30:43', '2007-06-08 14:30:43', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/06/08/chapped-lips/', 0, 'post', '', 1);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(151, 2, '2007-07-02 15:19:16', '2007-07-02 15:19:16', 'I believe I''m going to have to start a series of posts to completely debrief the past few weeks of what I have soaked in and how I have changed. Hopefully, it will add some kind of revelation to your life in some way. It sure changed mine.\n\nI''m not sure where to begin. Hm - I''ll start with this past Tuesday night. Last week I had the privilege of getting to know a beautiful woman, Ellen Stamps. She''s a dutch woman, among many other things, and by God''s direction ended up spending 9 years working alongside Corrie Ten Boom. If you don''t know who Corrie Ten Boom is, pick up <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=2oZ2AAAACAAJ&amp;dq=corrie+ten+boom+the+hiding+place">The Hiding Place</a>. What an incredible woman. Anyway, by the end of the week, she and I were on the terms of, "my Lauren" and "my Ellen". [add dutch accent]\n\nOn Tuesday, this woman showed me how to love. She displayed it <em>so</em> simply and <em>so</em> beautifully. After the evening talk on the night of silence (where the whole camp is silent to listen, pray and write letters to God), we talked for almost an hour. (Yes, we <em>talked</em> on the night of silence, but didn''t God heal on the sabbath?) Anyway, I wasn''t even expecting to talk with her like this.\n\nAfter chit chatting about where we''re from, who we are and such - she looked me in the eye and asked me this question:\n<p align="center"><strong>"Who does God want you to <em>be?</em>"</strong></p>\n<p align="left">Who does God want me to <em>be??</em> So much I have talked about <em>being</em> instead of<em> doing</em>, but this time, it really sunk in. So many times you''re asked, "<em>What does God want you to do?</em>" We''re all so stuck on this "doing" thing - that we haven''t found out who God wants us to be. What if everything you <em>did</em> was taken away? Where would your identity be then? Who would you be? This has strongly struck home for me because I''m there right now. Everything certain has been taken away and I''m left with... just me and God.</p>\n<p align="left">I''m not talking about our identity in Christ or anything, I''m talking about something maybe even deeper. I honestly can''t answer the question with words - it''s something you can only find out to live out. And at this point, I''m finding it. I don''t expect it to come overnight, it''s going to take so much time that.... I changed the "plan" of this coming year.</p>\n<p align="left">My decision, realistically, honestly doesn''t make sense. I had a plan. It was comfortable. It was logical. It was... good. I mean, what''s better than going to art school online, traveling around and taking photos everywhere, right? Well, I guess there''s something better.</p>\n<p align="left">I''ve never known so strong in me that I wasn''t supposed to do something. I had been waiting for an answer... waiting.. and waiting.. and waiting - and finally, I just had to make a decision. I''ve stuck with that decision, and it was a good decision. But in my heart, I felt something missing - but I had no idea what it was... and still don''t.</p>\n<p align="left">I don''t know where I''m going to be next year. I don''t know who I''m going to meet. What job I''ll have, if any. If I''ll end up going to school somewhere. If I''ll take a year off. Where I''ll travel. Everything is up in the air - <em>and I''ve never been happier. </em></p>\n<p align="left">Why take the joy out of life and make it so certain? Maybe I missed the uncertainty, maybe I missed having to fully trust God, maybe I just needed to fully trust God again... all I know is that there''s something even better for me.</p>\n<p align="left">Trust me, it''s weird coming home from your favorite place and your favorite people to... well, nothing. Nothing is expected of you, no job to need you back, no school to start in the fall, no place to go, money is needed but you''re unsure of where to work. Naturally, it would seem absolutely horrible, but it''s not.</p>\n<p align="left">Ellen triggered this in my heart and she didn''t even know it. Much more was said, much, much more.</p>\n<p align="left">See, my dear friend, Jessie, will be in Nicaragua for 5 weeks. She left this morning. A lot is uncertain and she couldn''t be happier. Keep her in your prayers.</p>\n<p align="left">I went to camp this year expecting and anticipating something and I got something different, but better. Everything I received was in a small package just for me - not some big, "wow" night that it seems a lot of us are looking for. I truly learned to find God in the small things.. in the unexpected places.</p>\n<p align="left">There was a man who sat by me every single evening talk. He''s almost 8 feet tall and disproportioned - his head is bigger than his body. But... <em>he has the most beautiful smile.</em> One night, we all stood up and held hands for prayer. He was hesitant to hold hands with anyone, so I made sure to take his hand and let him know it was okay. His hand engulfed mine. He looked at me and smiled so big - and I smiled the biggest I could right back. It was a cool moment. The last day, he came up to me and said, "I don''t think you know what it meant to me when you took my hand and smiled at me so beautifully like you did. Some have told me I have a beautiful smile, but you... you have the most beautiful smile." He teared up and so did I. I had no idea.</p>\n<p align="left">I found another small package when it would storm hard every single day at 3:30-4 o''clock right before prayer group... and we would have to run with towels and umbrellas over our heads through the camp. We would get caught different places and end up exactly where God wanted us to be... haha.</p>\n<p align="left">...and when you''re late for creatives (which, by the way, we had creative art, music, drama, journaling and writing) you make your own creative. Tommy and I did that so many times. We would dodge into Chilton and pick up guitars and swap to the piano when we wanted. Those were the most amazing times. Every time we play music together, we end up writing these crazy songs that we can never remember. I''ve never in my life flowed with someone like that. Songs would literally last for an hour straight.</p>\n<p align="left">Â </p>\n<p align="left">Well, I''ll save the rest for the next part of this "series" so to speak - of just - learning how to be. There''s much more to be said, I''ve only opened part of the beginning of it.</p>\n<p align="center"><strong>TO SEE CANDID PHOTOS FROM CAMP GO TO MY ALBUMS:</strong></p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/album.php?aid=2000049&amp;l=8064b&amp;id=1592310016">Shrine Mont CFO Part 1</a></p>\n<p align="center"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/album.php?aid=2000050&amp;l=db572&amp;id=1592310016">Shrine Mont CFO Part 2</a></p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">love.</p>\n<p align="center">-lauren</p>', 'Being - Part 1', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'being-part-1', '', '', '2007-07-02 15:19:16', '2007-07-02 15:19:16', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/07/02/being-part-1/', 0, 'post', '', 1);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(161, 2, '2007-07-14 04:13:47', '2007-07-14 04:13:47', '<p align="center"><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/804994850/"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/804994850_42757bbb63.jpg" alt="" /></a></p>\nI haven''t found a place where I''m completely fulfilled yet. And what I mean by ''place'' is not in a physical sense - it''s everything but.\n\nI find myself migrating tward something I don''t want. On the way to find identity, you place safety nets to catch you if you fall and safety blankets to curl up with when you don''t have anything else t turn to in times of grief.\n\nSeems to me that I''m building a name for myself that won''t last. It will fail me and cannot (and should not) be a safety net. My only safety net should be in one Name. Honestly, that Name should even be a safety net - it should rather be my constant shelter.\n\nI can''t rely on myself. I can''t and I shouldn''t be, and I know I have been. I''m not "throwing in the towel" I''m picking up something new and doing away with the old.\n\nMakeup (for us ladies) is also something of safety... a blanket in this sense. If you walk ut of the house without it, even powder, you feel... naked. I think it''s been turned into what <em>is</em> our beauty, not what <em>defines</em> our beauty.\n<p align="center">I''ve heard this too many times:</p>\n<p align="center">"What if someone really sees me like this -who I really am? They wouldn''t like/love me the same - or not at all."</p>\n<p align="center">---</p>\n<p align="center">Sex is not going to fulfill you.</p>\n<p align="left">The "love" that you''re searching for won''t fulfill you, either. It''s taken me awhile to see that (the latter statement). There''s only One Who knows love - His name <em>is</em> Love.</p>\n<p align="left">We love because He first loved us. Without that love (and loving with that love) <em>we''re nothing.</em></p>\n<p align="center">I don''t want to be nothing.</p>\n<p align="left">Yet, I don''t want to be something I''ve created for myself, either. Without a proper balance of His love and relation in my life, everything goes off.</p>\n<p align="left">It''s not going to be an easy ordeal to just ''let go'' of these safety nets and blankets I''ve held so dear. They honestly are my worst enemy. It''s funny how we fall into these things, isn''t it?</p>\n<p align="center">Our ways are not Your ways.</p>\n<p align="left">You can even have a friendship or possession be your safety net/blanket. You have trouble letting it go, even if you know it''s for you good, because it makes you the most vulnerable. None of us like being vulnerable but we still long for it. It''s something we need. It''s a place where we don''t have to be anyone, there''s no pressure and perfect acceptance.</p>\n<p align="center">...maybe this is the place I''m looking for. What we''re all looking for.</p>\n<p align="left">Maybe if we''re just accepted enough, or acknowledged enough or loved enough that that would be our place of vulnerability.</p>\n<p align="left">No. I do not believe so. It''s a false vulnerability with plenty of safety nets and blankets.</p>\n<p align="left"><strong> No more.</strong> <em>Hello, I''m Lauren and I''m a beautiful mess who''s in search of a deeper sense of self in the unending love of a Savior. </em></p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>I''m awkward and have a dry, gullible sense of humor.</li>\n	<li>I''m tall and have never had trouble with my weight - but plenty of trouble with my spine.</li>\n	<li>I have hazel eyes - and I say "hazel" because brown could sound too generic.</li>\n	<li>I have <em>dark</em> brown hair - because just brown could, again, be too generic.</li>\n	<li>I have only lived in one town my whole life.</li>\n	<li>The only time I''ve moved was in the same neighborhood up the street.</li>\n	<li>I have no been out of the country (except for Canada) but have a strong longing to travel and experience culture.</li>\n	<li>I need change but I hate it.</li>\n	<li>I''ve always had a fear of cutting my long hair off - so I did it this past winter.</li>\n	<li>I''ve never had a class in photography. I''m completely self taught - always observant, always listening.</li>\n	<li>I read photo manuals for fun.</li>\n	<li>I don''t believe in superstitions - I''m writing this on Friday the 13th and I''ve also broken plenty of mirrors for art projects.</li>\n	<li>I grew up being a massive tomboy. I even disguised myself and was believed.</li>\n	<li>I don''t let a lot of people truly get close to me - there are are only a certain few.</li>\n	<li>I am a virgin and sometimes when I meet new people, I feel like they can see through me because of my innocence (innocence is vulnerable).</li>\n	<li>I simply want to be free of the fear of man and your thoughts of me.</li>\n	<li>I <em>really</em> love Jesus. Really.</li>\n</ul>\n<p align="left">I have nothing more to say. Forgive this abrupt ending.</p>\n<p align="left"><em>please just <strong>love</strong></em>.</p>', 'Safety Nets and Blankets', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'safety-nets-and-blankets', '', '', '2007-07-14 04:13:47', '2007-07-14 04:13:47', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/07/14/safety-nets-and-blankets/', 0, 'post', '', 11);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(180, 2, '2007-07-27 20:45:28', '2007-07-27 20:45:28', 'listen to: <a href="http://myspace.com/andrewstonestreetmusic">timeless</a>.\n\nA lot of things have been running through my head lately. Things I''ve experienced, things I''ve been through, hardships, good memories and bad, everything you can imagine.\n\nWhile driving to Lowes and back from Lowes buying paint supplies for our unfinished basement (which we are finally finishing) I got to thinking these things again... and how I handle it.\n\nI''m one when I go through hard things, I withdraw - from everything. I just go hide away for awhile for a few hours, or a few days... or even a few weeks. When there has been so much rapid change all at once, I freak out. This has happened frequently to me when I least expect it and has happened in the recent past (pretty much being thrown into the unknown and living in the unknown for months now).\n\nWhen I drive, I like to watch people. My town is famous for traffic - morning traffic, late-afternoon traffic and evening traffic. If you catch an in between time, you''re golden. Anyhow, I intentionally glance at those behind me, driving past me on the left and sometimes unintentionally glare. I wonder things like, "I wonder what they''re thinking at this moment" or, "I really wonder if they''re having a good or bad day..." or something of that nature. Then, I glance in the rear view mirror and look at myself. I wonder what people see when they look at me. Someone who is going through a lot needing just a moment of your time and listening ear, or someone who has it all together or... well, there are endless possibilities. I just wonder, though... what I look like when I walk into Lowes alone thinking all of these thoughts of rapid change, wishing I didn''t naturally withdraw, etc. I wonder.\n\n...and if I''m like this - just someone who needs a listening ear once in awhile - and I''m a 5 foot 10 inch dark-haired girl with a camera strapped around her neck most of the time and slip on ballerina-cut shoes with a scarf in her hair... I guess I don''t really look like the "type" who needs "help."\n\nMaybe this is why I wonder so much about what the guy in the drive-thru window is thinking when he gives me my food and barely looks me in the eye adding, "Mild or hot sauce?" I don''t know. Just something to think about. I think the people we least expect are the people who need something the most. I''m not saying that we shouldn''t help those who are in apparent need, but we also need to try and look past the facade of those who appear to have it all together.\n\nI find this to happen a lot in church. I''m not talking about one particular church, just the church in general (and God be with the church). But seriously, I hear too often mentoring the youth that I do, "I can''t say what I really feel because well, I''m the elder''s daughter." This shouldn''t be so. People are people. We need each other.\n\nI hate hearing/having the pressure of this "identity" we seem to invisibly have and if we let down that "identity" (that either we or others have given us) something bad will happen. Someone will talk about us (even more than we are now) or just change their view of us. The church should be one of the most <em>safe</em> places for anyone and everyone - and even if it''s unintentional, we glare sometimes at those around us wondering their thoughts... wondering if they could be going through something similar to us, wondering if maybe, just maybe, they would listen. Can we please become more of a <em>listening</em>, <em>accepting</em> people? <em>Please</em>?\n\nI''ve also figured out today that I love working with youth. I thrive in it, even though it can be crazy and hard - but so rewarding. I''m striving to become a listening, accepting person - and I''m still far from where I want to be. I love those conversations in the car for an hour in my driveway, or on the back steps of an apartment building, or even in a witness interrogation room. No matter where you are, you are demanded (especially with youth) to <em>be real</em>. Up front they know I don''t have all the answers, but I''ll help them find the answers.\n\nAll I have, really, is a compassionate heart wanting to be that person who helped me through depression, who helped me through abuse, who listened when I called at 3 in the morning or on their work lunch break. I want to be that person who, when I drove to their house at midnight and knocked on their door to stay on their couch, they opened their home and their arms to me. I want to be that person. I am more than thankful having gone through what I''ve gone through. It has made me a better person today - a person who is more aware and sensitive... <em>because I was the girl who they would least expect</em>.', 'Compassion, Listening and Awareness', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'compassion-listening-and-awareness', '', '', '2007-07-27 20:45:28', '2007-07-27 20:45:28', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/07/27/compassion-listening-and-awareness/', 0, 'post', '', 5);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(187, 2, '2007-08-06 04:50:20', '2007-08-06 04:50:20', '<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/1023130563_eaadf2af67.jpg" alt="" /></p>\nI heard this story recently about a little boy who was asked once what his Mom''s favorite thing to do with him was. He replied, "Cleaning me up." I found that to be surprising... until it was a bit clarified.\n\nLater, they told his Mom was he had said was their favorite thing to do together was. She laughed - it really wasn''t her favorite thing <em>at all</em>. But she realized something. That was the time where she held her son the most - right after ''cleaning him up.''\n\nIt really struck me. I ask God to hold me a lot, to be near to me a lot, to let me know His love a lot. Something clicked in my mind at that moment. When I ask God to hold me - which would be the nearest to Him - that I would have to be "clean" to be near to such a Holy God, right?Â  Wouldn''t He have to, in a sense, ''clean me up'' beforehand? So in essence, when I''m asking God to be near to me/me near to Him/to hold me, I''m asking Him to ''clean me up.''\n\nOne of my life verses has always been, "Blessed are the pure in heart for they will see God."\n\nLet me repeat that with emphasis, "Blessed are the pure in <em>heart</em> for they will <em>see</em> God."\n\nWe see with our hearts (or we should). Maybe that''s why God put so much emphasis on guarding your heart for from it flow the springs of life. [or try the esv: "keep your heart with all vigilance, for from it flow the springs of life"]\n\nI need vision. We all need vision. And I''m not talking about a natural kind of vision. I''m talking about the vision that comes from the heart... where all your passion is stored.\n\nI bought a book the other day. Ever sense I heard it was coming out, I''ve had some type of interest in reading it. <em>Sex God</em> by <em>Rob Bell</em>. I honestly haven''t started reading it yet, but the titles of the chapters are intriguing to me (God Wears Lipstick?) Anyhow, we''ll see how that goes.\n\nThat book has a lot to do with vision. Repeat the verse above in your mind. It''s all connected and all extremely important. It''s sad this isn''t thought of more. I''m guilty, just like everyone else, of having an impure heart. A heart blocked from clearly seeing God.\n\nJust for the record I believe hearing is seeing and seeing is hearing. They cannot be separated. Apparently, <em>Sex God</em> is all about how sex and spirituality are intertwined without a doubt cannot be separated. Interesting. <em>It''s all connected.Â </em>\n\nI''m not sure how I got on the subject of sex by talking about vision. Somehow, it made sense while I was writing all of this out. I''ve taken a break, come back, talked with a few people, come back and wrote some more, another break, and more writing. All of this has been rolling around in my mind most of the day.\n\nI long to be truly pure in heart. In every since of the word. Pure.... <em>pure. </em>Down to the motive of my heart.\n\nAs I''ve stated many times, transition is something I know all too well these days. Let me explain.\nI''ve finished school. I''m not going to any other school at this point. I''ve got a job and looking for another. My church at this point is considering moving to a warehouse and changing our purpose and everything we''re about. I''ve been praying and fasting about it. God has me here still for a reason. I''m still trying to figure out that reason(s) - and it comes one day at a time.\n\nLast night I was thinking about how Jesus lived. I mean, really lived. He knew He had three years for all his ministry, and He never rushed. He was all about the journey, not the destination. I visualize Jesus "gliding" as He walked. Weird, I know, but true. Watch the Gospel of John, it''s pretty neat. Maybe you''ll see what I mean by gliding.\n\nI want to glide. I have time. I have time to meet everyone I need to meet. I have time to have long conversations. I have time to listen. I have time to be with the people I really love and not try to "do, do, do" for God. The more and more I think about it, the more it doesn''t make sense. <em>God is a relational God.</em> Why are we trying to live as if we can move the heavens with formulas?\n\nSo, as I''m being what God wants me to be, I want to be where He wants me to be. I''m here (in this geographic area) until this winter. From there, we''ll see. I''ll be traveling to different cities and places seeing what God has. It''s going to be good whatever it is.\n\nSo I need vision - His vision.\n\n<em>Hold me, God.\nWalk with me, God.\nClean me up, God.\nGuard my heart, God.</em>', 'Vision;', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'vision', '', '', '2007-08-06 04:50:20', '2007-08-06 04:50:20', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/08/06/vision/', 0, 'post', '', 5);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(193, 2, '2007-08-10 05:19:27', '2007-08-10 05:19:27', '<p align="center">Tonight, we honored by Dad''s birthday with a big bash at our house. <em>\nThis is how we do parties</em>:</p>\nFood. Conversation. More food. More conversation. Drift into the living room collecting instruments. Sing, play, laugh, repeat. This will go on for hours until we feel like... well, finished. Sometimes, if you''re lucky, some of us (including the attendees) will dance - interpretively. We''re entertained, to say the least.\n<p align="center">A few photos of the evening for your enjoyment:</p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0306.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0308.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center">Shannon likes to play with me.</p>\n<a href="http://flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1067476401/in/photostream/"></a>\n\n<a href="http://flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1067476401/in/photostream/">\n<p style="text-align:center;"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0311.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n\n</a>\n\nÂ \n\n<p align="center">Table #1\n(Table #2 not shown. Too embarrassed, ha. I should of used force.)</p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0315.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center">Anna and Ethan. Cool people.</p>\n<p style="text-align:center;"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0326.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n\n<p align="center">Hello, high ceilings and bright yellow walls -\nI wake up to  you every morning and you make my eyes hurt.</p>\n<p style="text-align:center;"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0343.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center">Melody - taken by Cait.</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n\n<p align="center"><strong>And now for a little bit of photobooth fun:</strong>\n(compliments of Andrew, Lydia and myself)</p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/MyPicture-5-1.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/MyPicture-4-2.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/MyPicture-4_3.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/MyPicture-4_2.jpg" alt="" /></p>\n<p align="center">[not my hand shown]</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n\n<p align="center"><strong>And heck, a bit of this evenings jamming (just for Andrew...)\nin video form. Nothing extravagant because the good-good stuff we must keep contained until further notice. You musicians know what I mean. </strong></p>\n<p align="center">[youtube=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2qMdEMusRGo]</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n\n<p align="center">Looking forward to tomorrow.\n-lauren</p>', '55 and Fully Alive.', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', '55-and-fully-alive', '', '', '2007-08-10 05:19:27', '2007-08-10 05:19:27', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/08/10/55-and-fully-alive/', 0, 'post', '', 2);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(203, 2, '2007-08-27 14:58:19', '2007-08-27 14:58:19', 'This post could quite possibly stir up some discussion.\n\nYesterday, Youth Sunday arrived. I was running around from the sound board, to behind the stage, to the back rooms... well, you get the picture. It was a really neat service. I brought my camera with me, but - it didn''t make it out of the bag.\n\nOn this particular Sunday, the youth  <em>do everything. </em>The dance/film team worked together and did a piece to Chaos by Mutemath. I choreographed it a few weeks ago, taught it the past two weeks and put the film together that would be played during the dance. It was all worth it. We''ll be doing it again in a few weeks... and that time, we''ll be filming it.\n\nWe had different youth speak about different mission trips and experiences they had this summer. The set up of the stage went like this: Tall, dark, wooden, square table in the middle of the stage, too dark, tall chairs to match and they spoke from there. They all did really well. I was proud.\n\nBy the way, we mixed up any ''normal'' service structure we had... this will be happening more often.\n\nOn Saturday, after all our final rehearsals and everyone had gone, I stayed in the sanctuary. I was exhausted, but good. I laid on the stage floor and covered my eyes with my arm. I ended up being there for <em>2 hours</em> and it felt like thirty minutes. No, I didn''t take a nap... I was just needing to be with God. So I laid there.\n\nStephen came back for me after those 2 hours and I got up with my mind full of thought - and he told me to go write it down upstairs on the sound board computer. So, I did. Another hour and two bottled waters later... I finished.\n\nSuddenly, I got this overwhelming feeling that I should speak/read this tomorrow in church. Heh, trust me I was already doing enough - dancing, playing keys and singing in the praise team. I kept this in the back of my mind and prayed about it that night. If I was supposed to, I would talk to Jesse (our youth pastor) about it and see.\n\nI get to church the next morning and immediately find out that Jesse isn''t there. His wife was finally having her baby boy, Jude (!). So, we had a gap in the service where he was supposed to speak about the vision of the church. <em>Interesting.</em> I went to Pastor Keith, talked with him and he gave me the go ahead. <em>What had I got myself into?</em>\n\nMy girls (13-15 year olds off the dance team) gathered around me and prayed for me. I have never been so blessed in my life. I had no idea how much I had affected their lives with the small things I did. I really, really love them.\n\nAnyhow, it came time for me to speak... I had finished dancing and I had a speaker in between that and when I spoke. I get up there and not one nervous bone was in my body. Something came over me when I walked up on stage. I sat down on that tall chair, placed my ''notes'' in front of me and it just flowed. I was a bit concerned because I was saying some... pretty offensive things in places.\n\nRead it for yourself - <a title="church-82507.pdf" href="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/08/church-82507.pdf">church-82507.pdf</a>\n\n- let me know what you think.\n\nI''m not one to be transparent like that in front of so many people at once. It was well received, though - a lot of people came up to me afterwards and asked for a copy of it. They also said my writing was like Max Lucado (they''re crazy) and they said it didn''t seem like I was reading... at all. I''m not one for public speaking much, but I don''t really mind it. It''s just not my favorite thing to do :)\n\nA quote I''ll leave you with... <em>Silence is pregnant with the voice of God.</em>', 'I heard You in the silence..', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'i-heard-you-in-the-silence', '', '', '2007-08-27 14:58:19', '2007-08-27 14:58:19', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/08/27/i-heard-you-in-the-silence/', 0, 'post', '', 12);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(212, 2, '2007-09-14 00:59:43', '2007-09-14 00:59:43', '<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/1375684358_41f10d5b13.jpg" alt="" width="348" height="263" /></p>\n<p align="center">my view every morning.</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center"><img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/1375684374_df1502e722.jpg" alt="" width="368" height="288" /></p>\n<p align="center">where I think + read every morning.</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">I''m a bit at a loss for words. All I know is I wish I could find a place that captured me. I need to get away for awhile, quite frankly. There seems to be some possibility on the west coast, some possibility in the mid-west... but even though my heart is needing a place to land, there''s still such a part of me here. I come alive when I see these girl''s faces - hearing their stories, listening to their hearts... I just don''t think I can leave that. There''s so much here, even though a huge part of me feels like there isn''t.</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">I just want to be fully alive - not almost, not partially. I''ve already got a Savior who has captured my heart and attention completely, but the passion and vision that I see in my heart have yet to be. Learning patience, perhaps?</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n\n<p align="center">I''ve been caught up in some battles lately:\nchurch vs culture</p>\n<p align="center">christian vs christian</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">It''s been interesting... and never ending. It frustrates me and at the same time, spurs me on with the little hope I have for change. There''s still hope in me for the church. There still is. I ache and mourn for the church and I honestly don''t ever think it will leave me.</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">Bottom line, I need a break. A short break, a long break... any break I can get.</p>\nI love leading worship.\nI love leading small groups.\nI love leading the dance troupe.\nI love working in the visual arts dept.\nI love it all... but I''ve come from a place recently where I''ve been deeply burned. Burned by ministry, burned by the church in the past... and it''s all happening so fast.\n\nAdding to it: I''m not in college right now. I know clearly that''s exactly what I''m supposed to be doing, but that doesn''t make it any easier. Drifting from one photography job to the next... applying for other jobs and getting no feedback... building a small business from the ground up with a low, low, low budget... attempting to pay the bills... the stresses of life are continual.\n\nEven though all of this is on my mind, I still find myself optimistic with a knowing of how sovereign God is and how I''m but a vapor (I''m reminded of this daily). There''s a peace that truly, truly passes my understanding...\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">All in all, what I''m looking forward to is the end of this month. The 23-26th (and beyond?) I will be heading into the mountains for a few days and breathing in that fresh air. Mm, yes. Onto Nashville from there, perhaps? Onto another destination thereafter? We''ll see.</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">Right now, it''s just been me and God. Me and my Friend. Me and my Everything. Through this crazy process of transition and change, He''s been my Constant and truly become my Everything (day to day).</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">Even though I may not have all the jobs I need to pay all of my bills pressing on me and I have no idea what school (if at all) that I want to go to next year and if the church will really, truly make it through this entire change... I''m okay and I will be okay. <em>It''s all good and by gum, He will provide. </em></p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">I''ve been known to take a different route all my life and I guess this time is no different.</p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>\n<p align="center">Forgive this blabbing about such and such.</p>\n<p align="center">-lauren</p>\n<p align="center"><strong>Â afterthought</strong>:Â  <em>for those of you who are coming to this site looking for photos and such, THAT website is underway. as for now, it''s linked to my blog. check back hopefully sooner than later for an actual website full of portfolio, contact, prices and goodies. love.</em></p>\n<p align="center">Â </p>', 'What? Hm? Yes? Okay.', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-hm-yes-okay', '', '', '2007-09-14 00:59:43', '2007-09-14 00:59:43', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/09/14/what-hm-yes-okay/', 0, 'post', '', 8);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(231, 2, '2007-10-12 04:14:08', '2007-10-12 04:14:08', 'Alright, so the last post didn''t do my heart justice. They haven''t for awhile. I''m sitting here writing poetry on large post-it notes. Yes, it''s true. I can''t seem to finish just one... so I''ll start another. It makes me feel better to waste post-it notes than pages in a journal - even though I know I should just ''waste'' them.\n\nMy faith grows, it diminishes, it leaps again, it plunges... but I keep seeking. Hopefully that''s worth something.\n\nSome days I have overwhelming realizations of how lonely I am... and I immediately shake it off. I don''t give it a second thought - until it decides to overwhelm me again. I''m not unhappy, though. Just, lonely?\n\nIt''s funny how we blame it on our emotions being unpredictable, so we put it all aside. That just doesn''t make sense to me.\n\nI don''t expect these thoughts to make sense. I''m just flowing in those "unpredictable" and "overwhelming" emotions. Forgive me in advance.\n\nI want to pour my life into another''s. <em>Someday.</em> Maybe I just haven''t found anyone truly worth while to pour my best into. <em>Not yet.</em> Or, I lack awareness. This has been hitting me recently pretty hard.\n\n<em>We all lack awareness. We look and do not see.</em>\n\nI want to see you. I really do. I just wonder if anyone really wants to see me... see me heart, see my soul.\n\nTruly <em>seeing</em> someone gives me hope for love.\n\nSay hello to part of a post-it note:\n\n<strong>Oh, dear // there goes all sensibility // I swore to myself this would never be // seeing you somehow gives me hope for love </strong>\n\nIt''s funny how the fear in our head talks our hearts out of loving. Not even romantically - just loving.\n\nI''ve been on this crazy thought for awhile about how this body is our shell. This body is what we''ve been given to love with, to express with, to glorify God with. This is what we''ve got. We can either be dissatisfied or do all we can to use our mind, will and emotion and these frail limbs to create a beautiful life - one that will be honorable, one that will (by someone) be remembered and cherished.\n\n<em>You do not have a soul. You <strong>are</strong> a soul. You have a body.</em>\n\nI''ve been living by this. Or, trying to. It''s sinking in slowly but surely. It''s changing the way I think, the way I love, the way I live. It''s simple - but sometimes, simple things change you the most. You don''t always have to be bold... you can be subtle and change the world.\n\nSee? I warned you. Thoughts. Not. Connecting. Really. Oh well.\n\nSongs on the mix tonight:\nSpeeding Cars - Imogen Heap\nHold You In My Arms - Ray LaMontagne\nAustralia - The Shins\nDoubting Thomas - Nickel Creek\nSundress - Ben Kweller\n\nMusic affects you. Maybe some of those explain my writing this all out.\n\nAll I can say is that I feel better. There''s... something to chew on. <em>Maybe. Hopefully. </em>\n\nSingleness is a beautiful thing.\n-lauren', 'Thoughts from Post-It Notes', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'thoughts-from-post-it-notes', '', '', '2007-10-12 04:14:08', '2007-10-12 04:14:08', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/10/12/thoughts-from-post-it-notes/', 0, 'post', '', 9);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(235, 2, '2007-10-22 04:37:04', '2007-10-22 04:37:04', '(as of now)\n\nFriday, I almost went out of town to surprise a friend in VA but last minute, we were unable to go. Simply put - not enough time with this special person for the gas/money spent. I''ll be going another weekend soon.\n\nSo, what do you do? You''re packed for a night and you have a car full of gas... but you have to be back Saturday afternoon. Hmm. -lightbulb- <em>Camping. </em>\n\n(<em>Shhh, don''t tell: but Brittany and I picked up Blacks on the way up. The only thing I''ll really smoke. I''m not a smoker. I just enjoy a good clove once in awhile.</em>)\n\n<a href="http://flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1682668665/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2029/1682668665_a8e11dce37.jpg" alt="" width="429" height="286" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1682668699/in/photostream/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2273/1682668699_1c06a6bb54.jpg" alt="" width="423" height="284" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1659281943/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2116/1659281943_c1f72daf87.jpg" alt="" width="431" height="287" /></a>\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1659281939/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2331/1659281939_8c70c00bfe.jpg" alt="" width="434" height="290" /></a>\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1660161156/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2398/1660161156_3bc30c759a.jpg" alt="" /></a>\n\nWe couldn''t find a tent. We didn''t have time to find a tent. We just needed <em>to go. </em>So, we slept in the back of my car. This place was about an hour away- not too bad. On the way there I wish my camera wasn''t in the back of my car while I was driving... I have never, ever seen a more gorgeous sunset in my life. Ever. And that''s saying a lot, I''ve seen a lot of sunsets. I''m sure Brittany will testify. We couldn''t turn on music. We couldn''t speak.\n\n<img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0364.jpg" alt="" width="404" height="268" />\n\n<img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/DSC_0362.jpg" alt="" width="403" height="268" />\n\nWe get there right after dusk, "set up" and roam around the campsite. My Mom had packed us this basket full of food- most of it a surprise (quite a pleasant surprise). We ate to our full, made an illegal fire (bonfires are ban in WV because of the drought) and talked. Then sat in silence.\n\nLately, both of us have been nocturnal. Almost every night this week I''ve been up until at least 3am working/editing, thinking, reading, in conversation with Andrew, playing music, sketching... anything you can imagine. It became routine that at 2:30, Andrew and I would get a ham and cheese sandwich. (<em>I make a killer ham and cheese sandwich</em>)  You get the picture. We came a bit tired physically and mentally.\n\nWe hit the sack by 11 and set the alarm for 6. To our surprise, we woke up automatically at 5. Ha. The stars were<em> so bright.</em> The greatest conversation happened between 5-7am. Sleeping in the back of the car was an experience, too. Lakeside, mountain view with windows. What could be better?\n\nThe sky turned from a dark, dark blue to a milky while and every 5 minutes it got brighter.. and brighter.. and brighter. I''ve come to the conclusion it''s easy to blow your mind if you really think about how the world is rotating and how dawn always comes. Always. You can''t keep it from coming no matter what you do.\n\nAs this kind of conversation continued about the earth, dawn, how we''re supposed to awaken the dawn (?!)... I realized I want to talk to an astronaut. A little goofy, yes, but this stemmed from the comment, "In 5 years you''ll see it all over travelocity - 4/day trip to the moon for your family! Only $700/person!" (<em>You never know.</em>) Anyhow, can you imagine actually <strong>seeing</strong> the earth and the vastness of space and have to come back and <em>live here?</em> I don''t know how they do it. My being would want to explode.\n\nAs all of this is happening in our minds, we decide that we want to read all the Scriptures we could find about the dawn, since we''re waiting for it to happen (it still being quite dark at this point). And to our disappointment, we picked up our journals from home and not our Bibles. Um. Not cool. We searched everywhere. We wondered how in the world we forgot them. We both own these small, travel-neat Bibles that are basically falling apart. I looked at Brittany and told her, "I''m aching." I couldn''t believe it. My body was seriously aching. Not because I didn''t sleep the greatest, not because it was too early, because I didn''t have the Word and I had, 5 minutes before, gotten so incredibly excited about reading it. I pray I never, ever forget that aching. It overwhelmed me. (<em>btw: when I got home, I found my Bible in the bottom most parts of my backpack. Interesting. Maybe I just needed to experience that aching</em>)\n\nRandom other thoughts from the conversation:\n-He calls himself the Morning Star?\n-the world is black and white before dawn - you can''t see color without light\n-there''s so much transition in the night: the earth constantly rotates, the sun sets and reappears. Every. Single. Day.\n-there''s an odd beauty at 5am.\n-there''s something about nature that awakens me and makes me go crazy. I love it.\n-I guess space would feel like looking at the ocean- a wide expansion of nothing and everything.\n\n<em>Straight from the journal</em>:\nWe packed in 5 minutes. No cell phone reception. No phones. No ''outside world.'' Nice. Scarves. Sweatshirts. Socks. No makeup. No mirrors. You feel alive; beautiful. Fog. Leaves. Dew. Fire. Reflection. Roof. Blankets. Books. Journals. Same pair of jeans as yesterday.\n\nLater that morning, we packed up whatever little we had and drove to a nearby old cemetery from the 1800s.\n\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1659281935/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2015/1659281935_edb433a698.jpg" alt="" width="395" height="263" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1659281933/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2298/1659281933_00f1a07f00.jpg" alt="" width="404" height="269" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1682668767/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2039/1682668767_b3e07a7c56.jpg" alt="" width="395" height="263" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1682668793/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2210/1682668793_0c0f4b3666.jpg" alt="" width="414" height="276" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1683200983/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2011/1683200983_a65923c874.jpg" alt="" width="407" height="271" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/elle_effect/1684095252"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2116/1684095252_11ec3ff385.jpg" alt="" width="423" height="282" /></a>\n\nI find that there''s not enough time to reflect. There''s always something to do. Always something going on. Always something. Our senses become insensitive and we can''t take life in the way we were created to.\n\nSo, in light of that... today was a day of reflecting and relating. After church, the Poole''s invited us over for lunch. You know, that Sunday afternoon <em><strong>lunch. </strong></em>;] We ate and were in conversation for hours both families together. After it all, it was undeniably nap time. Without a lot of discussion, we all (meaning 7 of us at this time, some had to leave) we piled pillows on the ground in the living room and grabbed bunches of blankets and quilts. We were out for 2 hours! Now that''s what you call communal napping, my friend. This should and shall be carried on every Sunday afternoon. All in all, we woke up, Katie, Mrs. Poole and I fixed an Italian dinner, we all ate again, more conversation and then old school game time. Remember Connect 4? Skipbo? Mmmhm. 10pm rolls around... we all head home. Goooood times. No photos, I''m afraid.. although I do believe Stephen took a few shots of us napping. Maybe those will be posted later.\n\nAs for now, I feel refreshed. I feel good. I feel tired at this "late" hours 12:30.. maybe Friday night ruined me? Hopefully. I need to be ruined on a continual basis. - in a good way, of course.\n\nLife is still constantly changing <em>(thank God</em>).\n\nAnd I guess for the somewhat, lack of entries, I posted a large one to make by accident. Hope you enjoyed and left with something.\n\n<em>love.</em>\n-l', 'best weekend ever', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'best-weekend-ever', '', '', '2007-10-22 04:37:04', '2007-10-22 04:37:04', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/10/22/best-weekend-ever/', 0, 'post', '', 6);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(240, 2, '2007-10-27 05:12:23', '2007-10-27 05:12:23', '<img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/34111459_ba69e5cad4.jpg" alt="" />\n\nThe light remained red. I sat there and sat there and <strong>sat there. </strong>The fog got thicker by the second.\n\nBut honestly - where did I have to be other than right here at this stoplight at this very moment?\n\nNo where. It''s midnight and I''m sipping apple cider and munching on the end of an oatmeal raisin cookie. I had just dropped off garbage at the dump. I had to be <em>no where.</em>\n\nThis wasn''t just some "long light" that tested your patience. I started timing it. At least 5 minutes had already gone by and time continued to tick.\n\nAll the sudden, I started applying this situation to my life. I''d inch forward and break, inch forward and break. Hmm. I''m inching toward the red light of potential opportunity and seeing when and if it will turn green at any given moment. I just can''t find it in me to make that left turn on a red light... even if not a single car has passed in 2 minutes. <em>I wait. </em>\n\nFloods of cars passed through to begin with... then silence; space. Out of no where, a few minutes later, more cars suddenly flooded the green light - passing me by. Hmm. <em>Maybe just for those few more to pass through, I''ll wait just a bit longer.</em>\n\nOkay, so this is becoming quite ridiculous quite quickly. A U-turn, perhaps? No - I''ll wait a little longer just to see if it''ll turn... it had been almost 10 minutes by now sitting at this four-way stop.\n\nI decided to pull the U-turn. The ne car behind me laughed, I''m sure, but an understanding laugh. I drove through the parking lot behind me and found a street - with no stoplight - that pulled into the main drag.\n\nYes. I''m on the main road heading home. Yes! Finally.\n\nBut, I wonder when that light turned green...\n\nI took the opportunity through a back door - on a back road. I wonder if I had waited. Would it of mattered anyway?\n\nIt''s possible, very possible, that I take small, simple situations like this and ponder too much. But usually the thoughts just hit me all at once.\n\nI''m not sure if I''m on a back road right now or nudging at the light for it to change... or being patient at the light and pondering.\n\nWhatever/whenever He wants. <em>Whatever, whenever.</em>\n\n(just soon, maybe?)', 'And the light remained red.', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'and-the-light-remained-red', '', '', '2007-10-27 05:12:23', '2007-10-27 05:12:23', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/10/27/and-the-light-remained-red/', 0, 'post', '', 1);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(254, 2, '2007-11-12 02:41:28', '2007-11-12 02:41:28', 'It''s Andrew''s birthday. He''s now 21. <a href="http://daleyhake.com" target="_blank">Daley</a> has been here since Friday. Packed, great weekend. Pictures to prove it. Back to work tomorrow... it was nice having a weekend off : )\n\n<a title="lauren3.jpg" href="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/lauren3.jpg"><img src="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/lauren3.jpg" alt="lauren3.jpg" width="396" height="266" /></a>\n\n<a title="andrew7.jpg" href="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/andrew7.jpg"><img src="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/andrew7.jpg" alt="andrew7.jpg" width="413" height="280" /></a>\n\n<a title="lauren21.jpg" href="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/lauren21.jpg"><img src="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/lauren21.jpg" alt="lauren21.jpg" width="414" height="278" /></a>\n\n<a title="lauren62.jpg" href="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/lauren62.jpg"><img src="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/lauren62.jpg" alt="lauren62.jpg" width="395" height="266" /></a>\n<img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/Photo50.jpg" alt="" width="384" height="288" />\n\n<img src="http://i71.photobucket.com/albums/i122/elle_effect_photography/Photo52.jpg" alt="" width="393" height="293" />', 'Look How Good We Look', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'look-how-good-we-look', '', '', '2007-11-12 02:41:28', '2007-11-12 02:41:28', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/11/12/look-how-good-we-look/', 0, 'post', '', 3);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(258, 2, '2007-11-14 03:06:50', '2007-11-14 03:06:50', 'with <a href="http://daleyhake.com">daley</a>, <a href="http://myspace.com/andrewstonestreet">andrew</a> and <a href="http://myspace.com/danieldixon">daniel</a>.\n\nI wrote this on the way here. I haven''t written poetry in... a few weeks... and I missed it. let me know your thoughts. and while your at it, check out mary oliver - daniel suggested her work and I like it. enjoy.\n\n<em>Awaken the coming dawn, love\nWith a whisper\nThe world awaits for strength in silence\nMovement that speaks for itself\nMorning rises with a word\nIts very presence overtakes the earth...\nagain\nalways new, ever changing\nwith a repeating routine -\nrest. sink. shift. turn.\nrotate. awake. expose.\na calling all its own\nbut without night...\nmorning would never be.\none with out the other is utterly\nin\ncom\nplete.\ntogether -\nyou have magic\nspiritually\ndepth\nwholeness.\nlove is as dawn.\nmysterious. beautiful.\nawakened and laid to rest.\nwithout night, it would not be.\nwithout hate, it would not be.\ncontrast serves its duty\na needed contrast\na loathed contrast\na misunderstood contrast\nlove will never be figured out;\njust as dawn will remain clothed in\nholy mystery.\nif we could understand love, its power would be\ngone.\nlove will never loose its power\nits beauty\nits mystery -\nI would never want its undistinguished language\nto change.\nI will live in it\nI will ride its harsh waves\nthat tame my restless soul, knocking\nbeautiful sense into me\nonce more...\nI need the night to appreciate the morning of\na new day.\n</em>\n-lauren', 'sitting in louisville, ky', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'sitting-in-louisville-ky', '', '', '2007-11-14 03:06:50', '2007-11-14 03:06:50', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/11/14/sitting-in-louisville-ky/', 0, 'post', '', 5);
INSERT INTO `wp_eqv5w1_posts` VALUES(259, 2, '2007-11-16 05:53:00', '2007-11-16 05:53:00', '<img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2414/2036134571_8a4bc5e394.jpg" alt="" width="404" height="268" />\n\n<img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2249/2036134577_4db3c0baa3.jpg" alt="" width="394" height="261" />\n\ndaniel dixon is... awesome. you need to check out <a href="http://myspace.com/danieldixon">his music.</a>\nI hope to see more of this kid in the future.  thanks, dan, for letting us crash at your place. it was lovely.\n\n<img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2323/2028657944_30e880d2bd.jpg" alt="" />\n\n...and these are the beautiful moments of our lives. the moments we take in slowly.\n\n<a title="d-d-a.jpg" href="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/d-d-a.jpg"><img src="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/d-d-a.jpg" alt="d-d-a.jpg" width="417" height="279" /></a>\n\n<a title="andrew_record.jpg" href="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/andrew_record.jpg"><img src="http://laurensusanna.files.wordpress.com/2007/11/andrew_record.jpg" alt="andrew_record.jpg" width="404" height="270" /></a>\n\nAndrew has been recording his Christmas album (released Dec 1st) at our grandparent''s home... nice feel, nice sound, nice vibe. I like everything about it.\n\nI''ve been writing a lot this week. I''ll be sifting through it all and posting some of it. It''s been a good, long day. Yesterday felt like 3 days in one. Today... yeah, pretty much the same.\n\nI''ve had quite a few of you respond about the $100/hr Sat deal... and I do believe that Saturday will in fact be Dec 1st from 12-5. Let me know soon again how that works for you - I have 2 booked for sure already.\n\ni love fall and the change it brings.\n-lauren', 'we have a writer on our hands', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'we-have-a-writer-on-our-hands', '', '', '2007-11-16 05:53:00', '2007-11-16 05:53:00', '', 0, 'http://laurenstonestreet.com/2007/11/16/we-have-a-writer-on-our-hands/', 0, 'post', '', 0);
